# Region Heterogeneity Test

This dataset has no ROI-level spatial coordinates (the GeoMx platform used here does not record them in this pipeline), so `region` — `Arteries`, `Capillaries`, `Parenchyma` — is the only spatial information available. It is nonetheless biologically meaningful for CAA: vascular vs. perivascular vs. parenchymal amyloid pathology are distinct compartments.

Every contrast above is fit *within* a region. `run_region_heterogeneity()` instead pools all regions per cell-type and fits:

```r
rel_abundance ~ group * region + (1 | Scan_ID)
```

`emmeans::joint_tests()` gives a formal significance test of the `group:region` interaction term — i.e. whether the disease/amyloid effect on a given cell type actually differs between compartments, rather than requiring a reader to eyeball whether per-region confidence intervals overlap. For cell-types with a defined interaction, post-hoc differences of the `Disease_effect`/`Amyloid_effect` contrasts are computed pairwise across regions (a "difference of differences") to show which region pair drives the heterogeneity.

Outputs: `region_heterogeneity_interaction_tests.csv`, `region_heterogeneity_posthoc.csv`.

---

# Cell-Type Co-occurrence

`run_celltype_cooccurrence()` (`R/cooccurrence_utils.R`) tests which cell types tend to co-occur within the same ROI, separately from the per-cell-type disease/pathology contrasts above.

Cell-type proportions sum to ~1 within an ROI (compositional data), so naive Pearson correlation between cell-type columns is biased toward negative values by that constraint alone ("closure"), regardless of any real biological relationship. A centered-log-ratio (CLR) transform is applied first — for each ROI, subtract the mean of the log-proportions across cell types from each log-proportion — which removes the sum-to-one constraint before correlating.

Correlations are computed separately within each `region` stratum (not pooled), because cell-type composition differs structurally by vascular compartment (e.g. SMCs are near-exclusive to Arteries) — pooling would mostly recover "which region is this ROI" rather than genuine co-occurrence.

Output: `celltype_cooccurrence_by_region.csv` (columns: `region`, `celltype_1`, `celltype_2`, `r`, `p.value`, `p_adj`, `n`).

---

## Effect Size

Effect sizes are reported as:
```r
log2_OR = log2(odds ratio)
```
Derived from model estimates:
- odds.ratio (if available)
- or transformed log-scale coefficients
  
## Post-hoc Testing

Post-hoc contrasts are computed using:
```r
emmeans::contrast()
```
Providing:
- Estimated differences
- Confidence intervals
- p-values
  
## Multiple Testing Correction

P-values are corrected using:
```r
p.adjust(method = "BH")
```
Applied within:
- each region
- each contrast type

